tp://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1475.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Medite's Response</span><hr size=1> I lead the Naggy raid where the shield was looted and dont' have time for a full post (darn work, they expect me to...work) but offer the following.<br>
<br>
The raid post stated Need Before Greed.  In addition, I was asked in the raid channel what the loot policy was and I reiterated that it was Need Before Greed.  Thus, it should have been clear to all who rolled that it was Need Before Greed.  I was not asked for an explanation of what Need Before Greed meant, and there was one item that nobody rolled on which was awarded to Cyraen  because they were the only one who needed the item.  Thus, at the time, it appeared to me that everyone knew the meaning of the term Need Before Greed. <br>
<br>
As to awarding the shield to a warrior, there is a rune IV effect on the shield (I love clicky things meself) and sometimes warriors like to play pally and bash things with shields to interrupt spell casting.  Did I think Knor would use it everyday and at all times?  No.  Did I think that he would use it?  Yes, otherwise I would not have allowed him to claim the shield in the first place.  <br>
<br>
Although there would certainly seem to be &quot;more need&quot; among other classes, I don't think that a loot policy can be that refined on an Open Raid.  (Syll has an excellent post on &quot;inventing fake need&quot; in another thread that is relevant to this point).  For example, we looted a Mithril Torque (+13 WIS and INT) and I (as a struggling smith who is convinced that high str does not help skill ups) rolled on the item because I need a great set of INT gear to help me skill up (195 and climbing).  I recently spent over 1k revamping all my INT gear and the best I could do on the neck slot was a +7int necklace.  Perhaps other classes would complain that a human warrior doesn't &quot;need&quot; the item as much as they do; but after spending thousands and thousands of pp to skill up in smithing (and other trade skills), believe me I &quot;need&quot; this neck piece. (Note to Jarkell: NO THIS IS NOT AN OPPORTUNITY TO SELL ME SOMETHING <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ).  If this were a guild only event, the Mithril Torque would have likely been awarded to another class.  However, on an Open raid, it seems the best we can do it state that it is Need Before Greed (or Can And Will Use) and rely on the honor of those involved.<br>
<br>
Open raids are (among other things) learning experiences for all involved.  As the leader of this raid, I have learned that it is perhaps better to call the loot policy Can And Will Use (to make it clear that only those who can and will use the item are allowed to roll on the item) rather than Need Before Greed.  Perhaps I can avoid a similar misunderstanding in the future by using this term instead.  Similarly, it is possible that Knor (and others) will learn from this experience.  For example, last week a member of Tribulation misunderstood the meaning of Need Before Greed and also rolled on (and won) a Mithril Torque.  After announcing that he had won the roll in guild chat and asking if anyone could use it, we informed this person that where the policy is Need Before Greed, you should only roll on the item if you can and will use the item.  This person returned the Mithril Torque to the raid leader, Tarin of Clan Twisted.  We all make mistakes (especially those who are new to Open raids) and before we crucify Knor and deem him &quot;Knor the Loot Whore,&quot; we should give him (and his guild) a chance to set things right.<br>
<br>
If Knor misunderstood the meaning of Need Before Greed, I am sure the posts on this board will serve to inform him of the meaning of this term.  Moreover, if he refuses to return the shield or invents a &quot;need&quot; (such as I &quot;need&quot; the pp), I am sure the damage to his reputation will also teach him a lesson.  <br>
<br>
Upon learning of this incident, I posted a message on Clan Twisted's board and asked them for their position on this matter.  I am awaiting their response and will keep everyone up-to-date on this issue.<br>
<br>
Medite Marconus<br>
